Gemini said
On Arch Linux (and most Linux distributions), Neovim follows the XDG Base Directory Specification. Your configuration files are stored in:

~/.config/nvim/

The Specific Files
Depending on whether you prefer the "classic" Vimscript or the modern Lua approach, your entry-point config file will be one of these:

Lua (Modern): ~/.config/nvim/init.lua

Vimscript (Classic): ~/.config/nvim/init.vim

[!NOTE]
Neovim will only load one of these. If both exist, init.lua is ignored in favor of init.vim (unless specified otherwise).

The "Proof" Config
To verify I’m not lying, let's create a minimal init.lua that makes two very obvious visual changes: it adds line numbers and highlights the current line you are on.

Create the directory (if it doesn't exist):

Bash
mkdir -p ~/.config/nvim
Create/Overhead the config file:

Bash
nano ~/.config/nvim/init.lua
Paste this code:

Lua
-- Enable line numbers
vim.opt.number = true

-- Highlight the line the cursor is currently on
vim.opt.cursorline = true

-- Set a visible sign column (the gutter on the left)
vim.opt.signcolumn = "yes"
Save and exit, then run nvim.

The result: You should see a column of numbers on the left and a horizontal highlight following your cursor. If you see those, Neovim is successfully reading from that path.

Pro-Tip: The "Truth" Command
If you are ever in doubt about where Neovim is looking, you can ask it directly while it's running. Type this inside Neovim and hit Enter:

:echo stdpath('config')

