how start neovim with an alternative config location

Gemini said
If you want to test a new setup without blowing up your existing configuration, or if you just like keeping things in non-standard places, you have a few ways to point Neovim elsewhere.

1. The Quick Way (The -u flag)
The easiest way to launch Neovim with a specific config file is using the -u (use) flag. This bypasses your default init.lua and loads the one you point to.

Bash
nvim -u ~/path/to/your/custom_init.lua
Note: This only changes the init file. It does not change where Neovim looks for plugins, swap files, or caches.

2. The Clean Way (Environment Variables)
If you want Neovim to treat a specific folder as its entire "home" (meaning it looks for init.lua, colorschemes, and plugins all in one place), you should override the XDG_CONFIG_HOME variable for that command.

Bash
XDG_CONFIG_HOME=~/my-alt-config nvim
In this scenario, Neovim will look for your config at:
~/my-alt-config/nvim/init.lua

3. The "Scoped" Way (NVIM_APPNAME)
This is the most modern and popular method, especially if you want to switch between multiple setups (like a personal config and a pre-built one like AstroNvim or LazyVim). Neovim allows you to change the name of the directory it looks for within ~/.config.

Move your alt config to ~/.config/my-alt-config.

Launch Neovim like this:

Bash
NVIM_APPNAME=my-alt-config nvim
Why this is better: It keeps your ~/.local/share and ~/.local/state directories separate too, so your alternate plugins and undo history don't get tangled up with your main setup.

Comparison Table
Method	Command	Best For...
Flag	nvim -u file.lua	Testing a single file quickly.
XDG Override	XDG_CONFIG_HOME=path nvim	Complete isolation from your Linux user defaults.
Appname	NVIM_APPNAME=folder nvim	Managing multiple "distros" (e.g., LazyVim vs. Personal).
Quick Tip: The Alias
If you find yourself using an alternative config often, add an alias to your .bashrc or .zshrc:

Bash
alias testvim='NVIM_APPNAME=my-test-config nvim'
