How the Folder Structure Looks
To keep them in parallel, your directory structure would look like this:

Plaintext
~/.config/
├── nvim/             <-- Default (launched by 'nvim')
│   └── init.lua
├── lazyvim/          <-- Alt 1 (launched by 'NVIM_APPNAME=lazyvim nvim')
│   └── init.lua
├── kickstart/        <-- Alt 2 (launched by 'NVIM_APPNAME=kickstart nvim')
│   └── init.lua
└── chadnv/           <-- Alt 3 (launched by 'NVIM_APPNAME=chadnv nvim')
    └── init.lua
Why this is the "Clean" way
When you use NVIM_APPNAME, Neovim doesn't just change where it looks for your code; it isolates everything.

By using different app names, Neovim automatically creates separate silos for:

Config: ~/.config/lazyvim

Plugins/Data: ~/.local/share/lazyvim

State (Undo/Shada): ~/.local/state/lazyvim

Cache: ~/.cache/lazyvim

This means installing a plugin in your "LazyVim" setup won't clutter or break the plugin list in your "Default" setup. They are effectively two different applications sharing the same binary.

The "NVIM Switcher" Script
If you start collecting more than two, typing NVIM_APPNAME=... gets annoying. Most people who run parallel configs use a tiny alias or a script.

You can add this to your ~/.bashrc or ~/.zshrc:

Bash
# Simple alias for your second config
alias lvim='NVIM_APPNAME=lazyvim nvim'

# Or a "Switcher" function
function nvms() {
  local config=$(ls ~/.config | grep -E 'nvim|lazyvim|kickstart' | fzf)
  NVIM_APPNAME=$config nvim $@
}
[!TIP]
If you have fzf installed, that nvms function will give you a fuzzy-searchable menu of your configs every time you want to start Neovim.

