splain that

Gemini said
That little snippet is a "config switcher" function. It turns a manual, clunky environment variable into a slick, interactive menu.

Here is the breakdown of what is happening under the hood:

1. local config=$(...)
This creates a local variable named config. The $(...) part is command substitution—it runs the commands inside the parentheses and saves the output to that variable.

2. ls ~/.config | grep -E 'nvim|lazyvim|kickstart'
ls ~/.config: Lists every folder in your configuration directory.

| (The Pipe): Takes the list of folders and shoves it into the next command.

grep -E 'nvim|lazyvim|kickstart': This is a filter. It says: "Only show me folders that match these specific names." If you add a new config folder later (e.g., astronvim), you would add it to this list.

3. | fzf
This is the magic ingredient. fzf (Fuzzy Finder) takes that filtered list and opens an interactive, searchable menu in your terminal. You use your arrow keys (or type to search) to pick which config you want.

4. NVIM_APPNAME=$config nvim $@
Once you hit Enter in the menu, the chosen folder name is stored in $config.

NVIM_APPNAME=$config: Sets the environment variable to your choice.

nvim: Launches Neovim.

$@: This is a shell wildcard that passes any extra arguments you typed. For example, if you typed nvms secret_file.txt, the $@ ensures Neovim actually opens secret_file.txt instead of just a blank buffer.

The Workflow Visualized
You type: nvms

The Menu pops up: * nvim

lazyvim

kickstart

You select lazyvim and hit Enter.

The Shell executes: NVIM_APPNAME=lazyvim nvim

One Small Tweak
If you want to make it even more automated so you don't have to update the script every time you add a new config, you can use this version instead:

Bash
function nvms() {
  # Find all folders in ~/.config that contain an init.lua or init.vim
  local config=$(find ~/.config -maxdepth 2 -name "init.lua" -o -name "init.vim" | xargs -I {} dirname {} | xargs -I {} basename {} | fzf)
  
  [ -z "$config" ] && return # Exit if you hit ESC in fzf
  
  NVIM_APPNAME=$config nvim $@
}
This version "scans" for anything that looks like a Neovim config, so you never have to edit the grep list again.

